    "id": 23533,
    "title": "Opinion Announcement - June 16, 2014",
    "transcript": {
        "title": null,
        "duration": 346.752,
        "sections": [
            {
                "start": 0,
                "stop": 346.752,
                "byte_start": 105472,
                "byte_stop": 0,
                "turns": [
                    {
                        "start": 0,
                        "stop": 8.372,
                        "byte_start": 105472,
                        "byte_stop": 139013,
                        "speaker": null,
                        "text_blocks": [
                            {
                                "start": 0,
                                "stop": 8.372,
                                "byte_start": 105472,
                                "byte_stop": 139013,
                                "text": "Justice Scalia has our opinion in case 12-842, the Republic of Argentina versus NML Capital."
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "start": 8.372,
                        "stop": 346.752,
                        "byte_start": 139013,
                        "byte_stop": 0,
                        "speaker": null,
                        "text_blocks": [
                            {
                                "start": 8.372,
                                "stop": 14.943,
                                "byte_start": 139013,
                                "byte_stop": 165345,
                                "text": "This case is here on writ of certiorari to the United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 14.943,
                                "stop": 23.714,
                                "byte_start": 165345,
                                "byte_stop": 200349,
                                "text": "In 2001, petitioner here, the Republic of Argentina defaulted on its foreign held debt."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 23.714,
                                "stop": 36.883,
                                "byte_start": 200349,
                                "byte_stop": 253012,
                                "text": "In 2005 and 2010, it restructured most of the debt by offering creditors new less favorable securities to swap out for the defaulted ones."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 36.883,
                                "stop": 43.028,
                                "byte_start": 253012,
                                "byte_stop": 277671,
                                "text": "Most bond holders went along but the respondent here, NML Capital did not."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 43.028,
                                "stop": 56.637,
                                "byte_start": 277671,
                                "byte_stop": 332110,
                                "text": "Instead, it filed 11 actions to recover on its investment and prevailed in all them, acquiring judgments totaling around $2.5 billion."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 56.637,
                                "stop": 65.297,
                                "byte_start": 332110,
                                "byte_stop": 366696,
                                "text": "Since Argentina has refused to pay those judgments, NML has tried to execute them against Argentine property."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 65.297,
                                "stop": 75.4,
                                "byte_start": 366696,
                                "byte_stop": 407134,
                                "text": "NML\u0027s most recent move, the subject of this appeal was to subpoena two New York banks where Argentina maintains accounts."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 75.4,
                                "stop": 96.826,
                                "byte_start": 407134,
                                "byte_stop": 492816,
                                "text": "Generally, the subpoenas seek the sort of information that would allow NML to learn how Argentina moves its assets through New York and around the world and accurately identify the places and times when those assets might subject to attachment and execution."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 96.826,
                                "stop": 102.825,
                                "byte_start": 492816,
                                "byte_stop": 516848,
                                "text": "Argentina and the banks subjected to the subpoenas, but the District Court compelled compliance."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 102.825,
                                "stop": 112.943,
                                "byte_start": 516848,
                                "byte_stop": 557286,
                                "text": "Only Argentina appealed arguing that the District Court\u0027s Discovery Order transgressed the Foreign Sovereign Immunities Act of 1976."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 112.943,
                                "stop": 115.144,
                                "byte_start": 557286,
                                "byte_stop": 566063,
                                "text": "The Second Circuit affirmed."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 115.144,
                                "stop": 119.349,
                                "byte_start": 566063,
                                "byte_stop": 582886,
                                "text": "We granted certiorari and today we affirm."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 119.349,
                                "stop": 127.334,
                                "byte_start": 582886,
                                "byte_stop": 614860,
                                "text": "We begin by assuming without deciding what the Second Circuit took for granted and what the government conceded here at oral argument."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 127.334,
                                "stop": 140.905,
                                "byte_start": 614860,
                                "byte_stop": 669194,
                                "text": "In the ordinary case, a District Court would have the discretion under the federal rules to permit discovery of third-party information bearing on a judgment debtor\u0027s extraterritorial assets."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 140.905,
                                "stop": 144.419,
                                "byte_start": 669194,
                                "byte_stop": 683196,
                                "text": "Argentina has not preserved an argument to the contrary."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 144.419,
                                "stop": 156.401,
                                "byte_start": 683196,
                                "byte_stop": 731157,
                                "text": "Therefore, the single narrow question before us is whether the Foreign Sovereign Immunities Act specifies a different rule when the judgment debtor is a foreign state."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 156.401,
                                "stop": 158.284,
                                "byte_start": 731157,
                                "byte_stop": 738680,
                                "text": "It does not."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 158.284,
                                "stop": 176.763,
                                "byte_start": 738680,
                                "byte_stop": 812554,
                                "text": "The FSIA replaced an executive driven factor-intensive, loosely common-law-based immunity regime with what we have repeatedly called \u201cA comprehensive framework for resolving any claim of sovereign immunity.\u201d"
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 176.763,
                                "stop": 189.11,
                                "byte_start": 812554,
                                "byte_stop": 861978,
                                "text": "In the post FSIA world, any sort of immunity defense made by a foreign sovereign in an American court must stand or fall on the Act\u0027s text."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 189.11,
                                "stop": 192.537,
                                "byte_start": 861978,
                                "byte_stop": 875666,
                                "text": "The Act confers on foreign states two kinds of immunity."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 192.537,
                                "stop": 202.451,
                                "byte_start": 875666,
                                "byte_stop": 915372,
                                "text": "The first, jurisdictional immunity was waived by Argentina when it executed the bonds that are sued upon here."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 202.451,
                                "stop": 217.806,
                                "byte_start": 915372,
                                "byte_stop": 976708,
                                "text": "The second, what our opinion calls execution immunity, generally shields property in the United States of a foreign state from attachment, arrest, and execution, and that\u0027s basically it."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 217.806,
                                "stop": 228.918,
                                "byte_start": 976708,
                                "byte_stop": 1021221,
                                "text": "The Act has no third provision forbidding or limiting discovery in aid of execution of a foreign-sovereign judgment debtor\u0027s extraterritorial assets."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 228.918,
                                "stop": 242.718,
                                "byte_start": 1021221,
                                "byte_stop": 1076391,
                                "text": "Far from containing the plain statement necessary to preclude application of federal discovery rules, the Act says not a word about post judgment discovery in aid of execution."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 242.718,
                                "stop": 249.407,
                                "byte_start": 1076391,
                                "byte_stop": 1103141,
                                "text": "Argentina would have us draw meaning from that silence, but its argument fails on its own terms."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 249.407,
                                "stop": 285.644,
                                "byte_start": 1103141,
                                "byte_stop": 1248068,
                                "text": "Even if Argentina were correct that FSIA execution immunity implies coextensive discovery in aid of execution immunity, the latter would not shield from discovery a foreign-sovereign\u0027s extraterritorial assets since the Act\u0027s main execution provision, a main execution immunity provision immunizes only foreign state property in the United States, but what a foreign state property that would enjoy execution immunity under the Act such as Argentina\u0027s military property."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 285.644,
                                "stop": 299.865,
                                "byte_start": 1248068,
                                "byte_stop": 1305015,
                                "text": "Argentina argues generally that if a judgment creditor could not ultimately execute a judgment against certain property, then it has no business pursuing discovery of information pertaining to that property."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 299.865,
                                "stop": 314.727,
                                "byte_start": 1305015,
                                "byte_stop": 1364470,
                                "text": "But the reason for these subpoenas is that NML does not yet know what property Argentina has and where it is, let alone whether it is subject to execution under the relevant jurisdiction\u0027s law."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 314.727,
                                "stop": 330.966,
                                "byte_start": 1364470,
                                "byte_stop": 1429358,
                                "text": "The subpoenas may turn up information about property that Argentina regards as immune, but that NML thinks is subject to execution, in which case, Argentina\u0027s self-serving legal assertion will not automatically prevail."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 330.966,
                                "stop": 335.368,
                                "byte_start": 1429358,
                                "byte_stop": 1447016,
                                "text": "The District Court in its sound discretion will have to settle the matter."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 335.368,
                                "stop": 338.921,
                                "byte_start": 1447016,
                                "byte_stop": 1461227,
                                "text": "The judgment of the Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit is affirmed."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 338.921,
                                "stop": 346.752,
                                "byte_start": 1461227,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Justice Ginsburg has filed a dissenting opinion and Justice Sotomayor took no part in the decision of this case."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            }
        ]
